title: az_FWSRefugeBdys_may05
abstract: This data set depicts refuge boundary information for National Wildlife Refuges, National Fish Hatcheries and USFWS administrative sites in Oklahoma, Texas, New Mexico and Arizona. The primary source for boundary information is the USFWS Realty and Refuge Planning programs (land status maps, planning documents, and legal surveys) in the regions.

abstract: This report presents data on the approximate locations and methods of discovery of 392 polar bear (Ursus maritimus) maternal dens found in the Beaufort Sea and neighboring regions between 1910 and 2010 that are archived by the U.S. Geological Survey, Alaska Science Center, Anchorage, Alaska. A description of data collection methods, biases associated with collection method, primary time periods, and spatial resolution are provided. Polar bears in the Beaufort Sea and nearby regions den on both the sea ice and on land. Standardized VHF surveys and satellite radio telemetry data provide a general understanding of where polar bears have denned in this region over the past 3 decades. Den observations made during other research activities and anecdotal reports from other government agencies, coastal residents, and industry personnel also are reported. Data on past polar bear maternal den locations are provided to inform the public and to provide information for natural resource agencies in planning activities to avoid or minimize interference with polar bear maternity dens.

title: 1 Arc Second National Elevation Dataset (NED)Data
abstract:
The National Elevation Dataset (NED) is the primary elevation data product
produced and distributed by the USGS. The NED provides the best available
public domain raster elevation data of the conterminous United States, Alaska,
Hawaii, and territorial islands in a seamless format.  The NED is derived from
diverse source data, processed to a common coordinate system and unit of vertical
measure.  All NED data are distributed in geographic coordinates in units of
decimal degrees, and in conformance with the North American Datum of 1983 (NAD 83).
All elevation values are provided in units of meters, and are referenced to the
North American Vertical Datum of 1988 (NAVD 88) over the conterminous United States.
The vertical reference will vary in other areas.  NED data are available nationally
at resolutions of 1 arc-second (approx. 30 meters) and 1/3 arc-second (approx. 10 meters),
and in limited areas at 1/9 arc-second (approx. 3 meters).  At present, the bulk of
Alaska is only available at a 2 arc-second (approx. 60 meters) resolution, owing to
a paucity of higher resolution source data, though some areas are available at resolutions
of 1 and 1/3 arc-second with plans for significant upgrades of the state over the next five
years.  The NED is updated on a nominal two month cycle to integrate newly available,
improved elevation source data.

title: Catalogue of Polar Bear (Ursus maritimus) Maternal Den Locations in the Beaufort Sea and Neighboring Regions, Alaska, 1910 – 2010
abstract: This report presents data on the approximate locations and methods of discovery of 392 polar bear (Ursus maritimus) maternal dens found in the Beaufort Sea and neighboring regions between 1910 and 2010 that are archived by the U.S. Geological Survey, Alaska Science Center, Anchorage, Alaska. A description of data collection methods, biases associated with collection method, primary time periods, and spatial resolution are provided. Polar bears in the Beaufort Sea and nearby regions den on both the sea ice and on land. Standardized VHF surveys and satellite radio telemetry data provide a general understanding of where polar bears have denned in this region over the past 3 decades. Den observations made during other research activities and anecdotal reports from other government agencies, coastal residents, and industry personnel also are reported. Data on past polar bear maternal den locations are provided to inform the public and to provide information for natural resource agencies in planning activities to avoid or minimize interference with polar bear maternity dens.

title: Cheatgrass mapping in Squirrel Creek Wildfire, WY in 2014
abstract:
This data bundle contains some of the inputs, all of the processing instructions and all outputs from a single VisTrails/SAHM workflow.  This model specifically includes field data of locations with >40% cover of cheatgrass (presence) and <40% cover of cheatgrass (absence).  Predictors included rasters derived from LandSat 8 imagery.  Details about both inputs are included in the associated manuscript.
The three bundle documentation files are:
1) '_archive_bundle_metadata.xml' (this file) which contains FGDC metadata describing the archive bundle.
2) '_archive_raster_inputs.csv' a list of the raster inputs that were used to generate these model results. These are not included in the archive bundle due to size constraints but are identified in this file as well as the metadata document.
3) '_archive_workflow_FinalModel.vt'where FinalModel is the name of the history node being archive in this bundle. Contains a VisTrails/SAHM workflow document which contains the workflow that was used to create these outputs.
The remaining data files are the intermediate workflow products as well as the complete spatial and diagnostic model outputs.

 The second row contains a 0 or 1 indicating wether the variable was retained (1) as a predictor in the models. This data bundle contains some of the inputs, all of the processing instructions and all outputs from a single VisTrails/SAHM workflow.  This model specifically includes field data of locations with >40% cover of cheatgrass (presence) and <40% cover of cheatgrass (absence).  Predictors included rasters derived from LandSat 8 imagery.  Details about both inputs are included in the associated manuscript.
The three bundle documentation files are:
1) '_archive_bundle_metadata.xml' (this file) which contains FGDC metadata describing the archive bundle.
2) '_archive_raster_inputs.csv' a list of the raster inputs that were used to generate these model results. These are not included in the archive bundle due to size constraints but are identified in this file as well as the metadata document.
3) '_archive_workflow_FinalModel.vt'where FinalModel is the name of the history node being archive in this bundle. Contains a VisTrails/SAHM workflow document which contains the workflow that was used to create these outputs.
The remaining data files are the intermediate workflow products as well as the complete spatial and diagnostic model outputs.

title: Cheatgrass mapping in Squirrel Creek Wildfire, WY in 2014
abstract:
This data bundle contains some of the inputs, all of the processing instructions and all outputs from a single VisTrails/SAHM workflow.  This model specifically includes field data of locations with >40% cover of cheatgrass (presence) and <40% cover of cheatgrass (absence).  Predictors included rasters derived from LandSat 8 imagery.  Details about both inputs are included in the associated manuscript (http://dx.doi.org/10/1016/j.jag.2017.03.009).
The three bundle documentation files are:
1) '_archive_bundle_metadata.xml' (this file) which contains FGDC metadata describing the archive bundle.
2) '_archive_raster_inputs.csv' a list of the raster inputs that were used to generate these model results. These are not included in the archive bundle due to size constraints but are identified in this file as well as the metadata document.
3) '_archive_workflow_FinalModel.vt' where FinalModel is the name of the history node being archive in this bundle. Contains a VisTrails/SAHM workflow document which contains the workflow that was used to create these outputs.
The remaining data files are the intermediate workflow products as well as the complete spatial and diagnostic model outputs.

title: Data from Monroe et al.: Patterns in Greater sage-grouse population dynamics correspond with public grazing records at broad scales
abstract:
The file package 'Data S1' contains data necessary to calculate 10-fold cross-validation scores for state-space models of male sage-grouse population trends in response to grazing level, timing, and NDVI in Wyoming, USA (Monroe et al. 2017).

The file package 'Data S2' contains data necessary for logistic regression analyzing effects of relative grazing index (representing the ratio of the reported livestock Animal Unit Months [Billed Use AUMs] to the maximum number of AUMs authorized by the Bureau of Land Management (BLM; Permitted Active AUMs) and grazing timing (% relative grazing index occuring before date of peak NDVI) on the probability of an allotment failing one or more Land Health Standard (LHS) the previous year. Relative predictive ability of models are then compared with a 10-fold cross-validation score.

title: Data file describing location and time of snake capture, including body size data collected in the field, for the manuscript “Ontogenetic and ecological variation in invasion risk of Brown Treesnakes (Boiga irregularis) on Guam”
abstract: Size structure within populations of invasive species may have consequences for relative risk at all stages of the invasion process, with implications for management interventions such as interdiction, suppression, and eradication. To assess relative distributions of invasive Brown Treesnakes among demographic categories of management interest, we undertook the most comprehensive and controlled sampling in >25 years of research into this ecologically and economically destructive introduced predator. We collected a seasonally-balanced sample of 100 snakes from each of 18 sites, stratified by six habitat types, encompassing the species’ entire extralimital range. Samples indicated significant differences in distributions of female and male snakes among management classes (juvenile, transitional, and mature) by site and habitat. We found substantial heterogeneity in localized population characteristics over relatively small geographic distances, only modest influence of habitat type, higher prevalence of reproductively mature snakes in savanna and urban habitats, and an alarmingly high proportion of snakes that are too small to be effectively targeted by current rodent-baited control tools (mean = 38.2%, range = 19 to 72%). Failure to account for such variability in high risk demographic fractions may hinder successful interventions.

title: These data describe stomach contents upon necropsy; this information was only used to adjust snake weight by subtracting weight of stomach contents, for the manuscript “Ontogenetic and ecological variation in invasion risk of Brown Treesnakes (Boiga irregularis) on Guam”
abstract: Size structure within populations of invasive species may have consequences for relative risk at all stages of the invasion process, with implications for management interventions such as interdiction, suppression, and eradication. To assess relative distributions of invasive Brown Treesnakes among demographic categories of management interest, we undertook the most comprehensive and controlled sampling in >25 years of research into this ecologically and economically destructive introduced predator. We collected a seasonally-balanced sample of 100 snakes from each of 18 sites, stratified by six habitat types, encompassing the species’ entire extralimital range. Samples indicated significant differences in distributions of female and male snakes among management classes (juvenile, transitional, and mature) by site and habitat. We found substantial heterogeneity in localized population characteristics over relatively small geographic distances, only modest influence of habitat type, higher prevalence of reproductively mature snakes in savanna and urban habitats, and an alarmingly high proportion of snakes that are too small to be effectively targeted by current rodent-baited control tools (mean = 38.2%, range = 19 to 72%). Failure to account for such variability in high risk demographic fractions may hinder successful interventions.

title: Cheatgrass mapping in Squirrel Creek Wildfire, WY in 2014 landsat layer R code
abstract:
This file contains the R code to produce the landsat derived predictors used in the models.  This data bundle contains some of the inputs, all of the processing instructions and all outputs from a single VisTrails/SAHM workflow.  This model specifically includes field data of locations with >40% cover of cheatgrass (presence) and <40% cover of cheatgrass (absence).  Predictors included rasters derived from LandSat 8 imagery.  Details about both inputs are included in the associated manuscript.
The three bundle documentation files are:
1) '_archive_bundle_metadata.xml' (this file) which contains FGDC metadata desribing the archive bundle.
2) '_archive_raster_inputs.csv' a list of the raster inputs that were used to generate these model results. These are not included in the archive bundle due to size constraints but are identified in this file as well as the metadata document.
3) '_archive_workflow_FinalModel.vt'  where FinalModel is the name of the history node being archive in this bundle. Contains a VisTrails/SAHM workflow document which contains the workflow that was used to create these outputs.
The remaining data files are the intermediate workflow products as well as the complete spatial and diagnostic model outputs.

title: Cheatgrass mapping in Squirrel Creek Wildfire, WY in 2014 'model' multivariate environmental similarity surface raster
abstract:
The multivariate environmental similarity surface provides an index that measures the similarity of each location to the training data related to the predictor variables.
This data bundle contains some of the inputs, all of the processing instructions and all outputs from a single VisTrails/SAHM workflow.  This model specifically includes field data of locations with >40% cover of cheatgrass (presence) and <40% cover of cheatgrass (absence).  Predictors included rasters derived from LandSat 8 imagery.  Details about both inputs are included in the associated manuscript.
The three bundle documentation files are:
1) '_archive_bundle_metadata.xml' (this file) which contains FGDC metadata desribing the archive bundle.
2) '_archive_raster_inputs.csv' a list of the raster inputs that were used to generate these model results. These are not included in the archive bundle due to size constraints but are identified in this file as well as the metadata document.
3) '_archive_workflow_FinalModel.vt'  where FinalModel is the name of the history node being archive in this bundle. Contains a VisTrails/SAHM workflow document which contains the workflow that was used to create these outputs.
The remaining data files are the intermediate workflow products as well as the complete spatial and diagnostic model outputs.

title: Edges of water in the North and South Units, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery
abstract: Edges of water in the Little Missouri River in the North and South Units (NU and SU), Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, were mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery (natural color, 1-m pixel size; see source data.) Daily mean discharge in the two park units on the dates of image acquisition (2010-06-29 in the NU; 2010-06-24 in the SU) was 2790 cfs in the NU and 3340 cfs in the SU. Uncertainty in mapping the edges of water is less than that in mapping the bankfull channel. These data provide average flow widths when discharge in the NU was within 20% of that in the SU. Average water-surface widths in the two park units were compared as part of an assessment of geomorphic differences that could contribute to differences in water availability to riparian cottonwoods.

title: Estimated bankfull channel in the North and South Units, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery
abstract: The estimated bankfull channel of the Little Missouri River in the North and South Units, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, was mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery (natural color, 1-m pixel size; see source data.) Average bankfull channel width was compared in the two park units as part of an assessment of geomorphic differences that could contribute to differences in water availability to riparian cottonwoods.  The bankfull channel includes point and mid-channel bars that are submerged during bankfull flow.

title: Extent of valley bottom in the North and South Units, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery
abstract: Extent of the valley bottom along the Little Missouri River in the North and South Units, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, was mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery (see source data.) Area of valley bottom was compared in the two park units as part of an assessment of geomorphic differences that could contribute to differences in water availability to riparian cottonwoods. Edges of the valley bottom were identified using the natural color, 1-m NAIP images supplemented by shaded relief images created from 10-m USGS NED DEMs and large-scale maps of surficial geology. The valley bottom extent includes terraces above the level of the present floodplain.

title: Little Missouri River channel centerline in the North and South Units, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery
abstract: The channel centerline of the Little Missouri River in the North and South Units (NU and SU), Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, was mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery (natural color, 1-m pixel size; see source data.) The centerline was identified between the edges of water mapped from the images, when daily mean discharge in the two park units on the dates of image acquisition (2010-06-29 in the NU; 2010-06-24 in the SU) was 2790 cfs in the NU and 3340 cfs in the SU. These data provide channel centerline length for computation of average sinuosity. Average channel centerline lengths and sinuosities in the two park units were compared as part of an assessment of geomorphic differences that could contribute to differences in water availability to riparian cottonwoods.

title: Valley bottom centerline in the North and South Units, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery
abstract: The valley bottom centerline in the North and South Units (NU and SU), Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, was mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery (natural color, 1-m pixel size; see source data.) The centerline was identified between the edges of the valley bottom mapped from the images. These data provide valley centerline length for computation of average sinuosity. Average valley centerline lengths and sinuosities in the two park units were compared as part of an assessment of geomorphic differences that could contribute to differences in water availability to riparian cottonwoods.

title: Riparian cottonwood forest area in the South Unit, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery
abstract: Areas of riparian cottonwood forest in the South Unit, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, were mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery (natural color, 1-m pixel size; see source data.)

title: Floodplain area in the South Unit, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery
abstract: Floodplain areas in the South Unit, Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, were mapped from 2010 NAIP imagery (natural color, 1-m pixel size; see source data.) The mapped areas were estimated to be active floodplain, excluding high terraces.

title: Ring widths of trees cored in 2010 at the North Unit of Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND
abstract: This metadata references a text file giving 72,689 annual ring widths for 649 cores from 433 cottonwood trees collected in summer and fall of 2010. The trees are located on the floodplain of the Little Missouri River in the North Unit of Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND. These data were used to reconstruct flow and climate as described in the Friedman and Griffin (2017) report and in other documents cited by that report. The file is saved in Standard Tucson format. The first column gives the name of the core. The core name begins with one letter describing the tree from which the core was taken. The letter F or P indicates that the cored tree was the closest corable tree to a randomly selected point on the floodplain. The letter C indicates that the cored tree was an additional old live tree cored to increase sample size in early years of flow reconstructions. Following the letter is a three-digit number uniquely identifying the cored tree. One additional letter is appended to distinguish the core from others taken from the same tree. The second column gives the calendar year of the ring whose width is listed in the third column. Entries in columns three through twelve (where present) are annual ring widths for successive years in thousandths of millimeters. The rightmost entry in each row is the ninth year of a decade (e.g. 1939). The value -9999 indicates the end of a core.

title: Ring widths of trees cored in 2012 at the South Unit of Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND
abstract: This metadata references a text file giving 21,662 annual ring widths for 194 cores from 105 cottonwood trees collected in April 2012. The trees are located on the floodplain of the Little Missouri River in the South Unit of Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND. These data were used to reconstruct flow and climate as described in the Friedman and Griffin (2017) report and in other documents cited by that report. The file is saved in Standard Tucson format. The first column gives the name of the core. The first two letters describe the cored tree. Trees whose names begin with SU are the closest corable trees to 75 randomly selected points on the floodplain. Trees whose names begin with CT are additional dead trees sampled, to determine the year of death, or old live trees cored to increase sample size in early years of flow reconstructions. Following the two letters is a two-digit number uniquely identifying the cored tree. Where more than one core was taken from a tree, one or two additional characters are appended to uniquely identify the core. The second column gives the calendar year of the ring whose width is listed in the third column. Entries in columns three through twelve (where present) are annual ring widths for successive years in thousandths of millimeters. The rightmost entry in each row is the ninth year of a decade (e.g. 1939). The value -9999 indicates the end of a core.

title: Sex Ratio of Cottonwood Trees at Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND, in 2012
abstract: This metadata references a comma-delimited file documenting the sex ratio of cottonwood trees at random points on the floodplain in the North and South units of Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND. These data were used to investigate the effects of age, height above, and distance from the channel on mortality of male and female trees of plains cottonwood (Populus deltoides subsp. monilifera) as described in the Friedman and Griffin (2017) report. At 75 randomly selected points at the North Unit and 74 random points at the South Unit, we determined the sex of the closest 20 trees. If there were fewer than 20 trees on the same fluvial surface as the random point, we determined the sex of all of the trees. Each row in the file gives information about a single random point, including the name of the point, its location measured precisely with a real-time kinematic global positioning system, distance from and height above the channel, calendar year of the center ring, number of females, males and trees of unknown sex, percent males, and total number of trees sampled.

title: Trees cored in 2010 at the North Unit of Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND
abstract: This metadata references a comma-delimited file describing 433 cottonwood trees from which cores were collected in summer and fall of 2010. The trees are located on the floodplain of the Little Missouri River in the North Unit of Theodore Roosevelt National Park, ND. These data were used to reconstruct flow and climate as described in the Friedman and Griffin (2017) report and in other documents cited by that report. Each tree in the file is described on a unique row. Trees whose names begin with F or P are the closest corable trees to randomly selected points on the floodplain. Trees whose names begin with C are additional old trees on the floodplain sampled, where available, to increase sample size in early years of flow reconstructions. The file provides latitude and longitude, in decimal degrees for each tree, an estimated date for the center ring of each tree, stem density near the random point (trees per square meter), diameter of the tree in cm at a height of 1.2 m above the ground, and the latitude and longitude of the random points.
